He heard the jeers and laughter of the bullies chasing him, taunting him with every step.

“Get him, get him”, yelled one of the rowdy goons thirty yards behind him. Victor tried not to look back and thought about the best route to get back home without giving the little gang any chances to cut him off using any of the little side streets.

Victor lived in a two-bedroom house in the Rio Azul neighborhood. Most houses had orange brick facades clumped together in long blocks that extended in all directions. If you walked down the streets of this neighborhood, like Victor did every day on his way to school, you would see one tree per block and a few tiny gardens that did little to bring the area to life during the week when most people were at work or at school.

It took Victor exactly nineteen minutes to walk from the front door of his house, turn at the corner, pass by the neighborhood's park, cross the pedestrian bridge over Nuñes Avenue, and then arrive at the District 6 School, where he spent most of his days. He also knew that on a rainy day, it could take him four more minutes to finish the same route, but since his mom made certain that he always carried an umbrella in his backpack, that was not much of an issue. Unfortunately, Victor did not have time to use the umbrella to protect himself from the cold drizzle that started half an hour before.

He ducked into Mr. Torres' garden, hiding behind a eucalyptus tree and several bushes. The bullies barely missed him as they ran past, searching for where he went. He held his breath, hoping they wouldn't notice the branches moving.

Victor looked around and was not able to see any of his classmates, like Jerónimo and Yurcenis. He usually saw them on his usual route, and they were nice to him, and they even shared a laugh or two, but Victor would not call them his friends, because his dad taught him that friends are the people who would stand by your side in your time of need, and in the last two years, he knew that he had to stand alone against his enemies.

You would think that an eleven-year-old boy would have no enemies, but you had not met Cayetano and his little band of miscreants. Cayetano lived a few blocks away from Victor in his parent's house which doubled down as a tiny vegetable store. Victor had avoided that spot for years after he noticed how mean Cayetano could be when his dad was not around. No one, not little kids nor grown-ups, escaped the little bully's “peculiar” pranks. Misses Fernandez had been attacked with rotten tomatoes at least twice last year. Mister Calderón habitually found his newspaper in his garbage can or completely soaked with muddy water. And the Castro’s pug, named Dulce, was terrified after Cayetano and his friends managed to completely wrap her in duct tape.

As soon as they were out of sight, Victor dashed across the street into the Mejia's driveway, hiding in their parked truck that, fortunately for him, was left unlocked for some reason. He slid into the space behind the front seat, taking off his backpack in a swift move and curling up into a ball. After a couple of minutes, the bullies came stomping down the street, still on the hunt. But they didn't look in the direction of the truck. The boy sighed in relief as they continued their chase.

His next move was risky, but desperate times called for desperate measures. He ran to the old abandoned church at the end of the street, lifting the rusted padlock and slipping inside. The front door screeched when Victor cracked it open, and he hoped that the rain covered his escape.

Victor would have never dared to enter the decrepit place if it wasn't for the urgent need to take cover from the rain and the mean group of kids. The church was crumbling, the roof had holes in it, the paint on the outside was peeling off, the tiny front yard was overgrown with weeds; the bushes under the front windows were brown. The white walls were worn from over a decade of sun and rain. The walls were falling apart with jagged holes and flaking paint.

As soon as he was certain that other kids were not around, Victor assessed the inside of the church. Old stacks of paper, broken pews and chairs, old trinkets that had been thrown away and left to decay but, incredibly, most of the stained colored windows remained unbroken. The smell of the wet asphalt from the street could not cover the moldy scent of the walls.

Victor's footsteps echoed through the empty church and his fear made him slow down. Dusty spider webs filled the antechamber where the Holy Water font was still standing, but there was enough light coming through the cracked walls and big windows for Victor to feel safe to hide. He dropped his backpack by his feet and clutched a piece of wooden furniture for protection, hoping the bullies would eventually give up their search.

Any moment, Victor expected his chasers to discover his hiding place. But after what seemed like an eternity, the angry shouts of the thugs faded into the distance. He was alone at last. Exhausted and shaken, Victor sank to the old floor and thought about how the problems with Cayetano started when Victor was eight years old. 

Almost three years before, Victor went out to play soccer with a few kids down the street. They just went to the empty grassy area next to the Castro’s house and set up a makeshift goal with two rocks. They took turns as goalkeepers and did not have even defined teams. It was a free-for-all score-a-goal however you can type of game. And then Cayetano joined the game.
